===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|abod|lang=enm}}, {{term|abad|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|*ābād}}, related to {{term/t|ang|ābīdan||to abide}}; see ''[[abide]]''. Cognate with Scots {{term|abade|lang=sco}}, {{term|abaid||abode|lang=sco}}. For the change of vowel, compare ''abode'', preterit of ''abide''.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} Act of [[waiting]]; delay. {{defdate|Attested from (1150 to 1350) to the early 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED>{{reference-book|editor=Brown, Lesley|title=The Shorter Oxford English Dictionary|origyear=1933|edition=5th|year=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford, UK|isbn =978-0-19-860575-7|pages=6}}</ref>
#* '''1590''', {{w|Edmund Spenser}}, ''{{w|The Faerie Queene}}'', III.viii:
#*: Vpon his Courser set the louely lode, / And with her fled away without '''abode'''.
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} Stay or [[continuance]] in a place; [[sojourn]]. {{defdate|Attested from (1350 to 1470) to the mid 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* '''1661''', {{w|John Fell (bishop)|John Fell}}, ''[http://archive.org/stream/a615775104worduoft/a615775104worduoft_djvu.txt The Life of the most learned, reverend and pious Dr. H. Hammond]''
#*: During the whole time of his '''abode''' in the university he generally spent thirteen hours of the day in study; by which assiduity besides an exact dispatch of the whole course of philosophy, he read over in a manner all classic authors that are extant{{...}}
#* {{rfdate}}, {{w|Henry Fielding}} (1707-1754)
#*: He waxeth at your '''abode''' here.
# {{context|formal|lang=en}} A residence, [[dwelling]] or [[habitation]]. {{defdate|First attested from around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{rfdate}}, {{w|William Wordsworth}} (1770-1850)
#*: Come, let me lead you to our poore '''abode'''.

